title: Update "node-fetch" typings
body:
Convert to external module and remove `namespace _fetch`
This is a breaking change, as people should use ES6-style imports now rather than `import fetch = require("fetch")` and the `_fetch` namespace; but as luck would have it, this also includes a major version bump.
I've tested this change out in [types-publisher](https://github.com/Microsoft/types-publisher) too.

title: Correction to array type for ProtoEnum in ProtoBuf.js
body:
The values field of the ProtoEnum interface should be an array not a single entry. This can be seen when using the Protobuf.js parser on enum fields where a file containing:

```

enum Priority {
    LOW = 1;
    MEDIUM = 2;
    HIGH = 3;
}
```

Is parsed to:

```
{ package: null,                                                             
  messages: [],                                                              
  enums:                                                                     
   [ { name: 'Priority',                                                     
       values:                                                               
        [ { name: 'LOW', id: 1 },                                            
          { name: 'MEDIUM', id: 2 },                                         
          { name: 'HIGH', id: 3 } ],                                         
       options: {} } ],                                                      
  imports: [],                                                               
  options: {},                                                               
  services: [] } 
```

see https://github.com/dcodeIO/ProtoBuf.js/wiki/Parser

title: Types 2.0
body:
case 2. Improvement to existing type definition.

Source: https://github.com/hapijs/joi/blob/master/API.md#errors
## Errors

Joi throws classical javascript `Error`s containing :
- `name` - `'ValidationError'`.
- `isJoi` - `true`.
- `details` - an array of errors :
  - `message` - string with a description of the error.
  - `path` - dotted path to the key where the error happened.
  - `type` - type of the error.
  - `context` - object providing context of the error.
- `annotate` - function that returns a string with an annotated version of the object pointing at the places where errors occured.
- `_object` - the original object to validate.

title: [types-2.0] react - better strict mode compatibility
body:
# index.d.ts - line 16, `Key` was changed to accept null, When you do `React.createElement(...)` and you do not supply a key, it becomes the value `null`. - line 40, `ComponentClass

`, when testing `React.cloneElement` which is able to accept `null` and `undefined`, had to add `any` type. - line 77, `DOMFactory`, using any `React.DOM.xxx` function to create an element. For example `React.DOM.div(null, undefined)` actually works and thus added. - line 96, a React child can be `null`. - line 202, the last [commit](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/commit/b329e7ec15c7a6dbebfca0e0ed916cb5f60f269a) added the return type of `null` to `SFC

` and in strict mode there was no longer the possibility to render the component any more, it will say `null is not a constructor function for jsx elements.`. A workaround is to convert it to an interface then overload the constructor function to have let `SFC

` to have the ability to return null, but leave `StatelessComponent

` alone. You now have 2 versions to work with, in strict mode `SFC

` will fail to render every time because of `null` return, but `StatelessComponent

` will work. - line 265, `ComponentSpec.render`, the render may return `null` like every other render. --- The rest of the files had to be adjusted accordingly when using `strictNullChecks`.
